## General Style Guidelines

We follow the [Mathlib style guide][mathlib-style] with some additions related to the specific patterns we use in verification. 

### Header and Imports

File headers of edited files should be of the form:
```lean
/-
Copyright 2026 The Beneficial AI Foundation. All rights reserved.
Released under Apache 2.0 license as described in the file LICENSE.
Authors: Joe Cool
-/
```
Any authors who have made significant contributions to the file should be added to the author list. They are added in chronological order based on when they edit the file. AI tools cannot be listed as authors. 

### Avoiding Flexible Tactics

Flexible (non-terminal) tactics make proofs fragile and harder to maintain.
Avoid them as much as possible:

- **`simp`**: Use `simp?` to obtain the explicit lemma list, then replace with
  `simp only [...]`. This makes the proof deterministic and resistant to
  changes in the simp set.
- **`simp_all`**: Same rule — use `simp_all?` to obtain `simp_all only [...]`.
- **`grind`**: Prefer more targeted alternatives (`omega`, `ring`,
  `linear_combination`, `decide`, etc.) where feasible.
- **`exact?`** / **`apply?`**: Use these *interactively* to discover the right
  lemma, then replace with the explicit `exact` or `apply` call.

When a flexible tactic is genuinely the best option (e.g. a `simp` that closes
a goal and whose lemma list would be impractically long), document why in a
short comment.

IMPORTANT NOTE: flexible tactics are only considered a problem / style guide violation IF there is a linter highlighting the issue. If there is no linter, the command is acceptable and does not count as a style guide violation!

ANOTHER IMPORTANT NOTE: Flexible tactics are only a problem if they are NON-TERMINAL. If a flexible tactic is TERMINAL (i.e., if it is the last command in a proof and leads to closure of the goal) then this will not lead to downstream maintenance issues and is thus FINE.

### Linters

Linter warnings should be **resolved, not suppressed**. Avoid `#check`/`#eval`
leftovers and `set_option linter.* false` unless there is a clear justification
documented in a comment.

### Heartbeats

Keep `set_option maxHeartbeats` increases to the bare minimum needed.
Use multiples of **200000** as a standard increment (e.g. 400000, 800000).
If a proof requires a very large heartbeat budget, consider refactoring it
into helper lemmas to bring the cost down.

### Formatting

- Lines should be at most 100 characters
- Imports should be listed immediately after the file header without empty lines.
- When adding definitions and theorems (except for spec theorems), follow the [Mathlib naming guidelines][mathlib-naming]. 

## Spec Theorem File Guidelines

- Each spec theorem lives in its own file together with any additional lemmas which are required for the proof of it, unless they can also be used elsewhere, in which case they should be placed in a central location.
- The file contains a module docstring which explains concisely the function via a mathematical natural-language description and includes the Rust source file path where the associated function is originally defined. The module docstring should appear immediately after the imports, but with one empty line between imports and module docstring.
  ```lean
  /-! 
  # Spec theorem for `function_name`

  Brief mathematical natural-language description of what the function is doing / its purpose.

  Source: "rust/source/path.rs"
  -/
  ```

- The file is named according to the associated function name but in UpperCamelCase. E.g., if the function is extracted in Lean to `from_bytes` then the file should be called `FromBytes.lean`. 

- The file must be placed in a folder which is named to match the Rust source file where the function is defined. This folder is then placed within a directory structure which mirrors the Rust source code directory structure. In case there are two identically named functions defined in the same Rust file, add a relevant prefix to create the Lean file name so they can be distinguished from each other.  

### Spec Theorem Style

All spec theorems should be stated using `⦃ ... ⦄` Aeneas WP syntax. The canonical layout is:

```lean
/-- **Spec theorem for `full::rust::function::name::including::module`**
• A suitable formulation of the always inherent "no-panic" condition
• Concise, precise, mathematical natural language description of post_condition_1
...
• Concise natural language description of post_condition_n
-/
@[step]
theorem fun_name_spec (a : argType) (b : argType) (h1 : pre_condition1) 
    (h2 : pre_condition2) :
    fun_name a b ⦃ (result : resultType) =>
      post_condition_1 ∧
      post_condition_2 ⦄ := by
  sorry
```

- Add the attribute `@[step]` so the Aeneas step tactic can find them. Start a new line after the attributes.
- The theorem name should be the name of the function with the suffix `_spec`. Note the identifier of the spec theorem should be the __full name__ of the function with this suffix.
- Open namespaces properly so that the identifier prefix is not cluttering the spec theorem code and yet the spec theorem identifier is the full identifier of the function with suffix as required. I.e., for a spec theorem for `crate_name.mod_name.type_name.fun_name` the theorem will be as in the example above and it is required to open `namespace crate_name.mod_name.type_name` earlier in the file and `end` it later in the file.
- Arguments and preconditions (i.e., `(a : argType) (b : argType)`, `(h : pre_condition)`, ... ) are placed after the name and on following lines.
- Immediately after the main `:` of the theorem start a new line and write the function application and WP binder: `fun_name a b ⦃ (result : resultType) =>`
- `result` should always be given its appropriate `resultType` (note that this requires brackets to parse correctly)
- Postconditions should be written as a logical conjunction via `post_condition_1 ∧ post_condition_2 ∧ ...` inside `⦃ ... ⦄`.
- The arguments of the spec theorem should be named exactly like the corresponding entities in the original function definition for `fun_name`.
- Indentation Structure:
  - `@[step]` tag and `theorem fun_name_spec` statement: 0 spaces
  - Arguments, preconditions and line with function application: 4 spaces
  - Postconditions `post_condition_i ∧`: 6 spaces
  - Proof body: 2 spaces
  
[mathlib-style]: https://leanprover-community.github.io/contribute/style.html
[mathlib-naming]: https://leanprover-community.github.io/contribute/naming.html

### How to merge the central comment block information into module docstring and spec theorem docstring

Many spec theorem files contain a central comment block of the following form (example for RistrettoPoint::add):

/-
natural language description:

• Takes two RistrettoPoints `self` and `other`
• Returns their sum as a RistrettoPoint via elliptic curve group addition
• Implementation: unwraps both points to their underlying EdwardsPoint representations,
  performs Edwards addition, and wraps the result back as a RistrettoPoint

natural language specs:

• The function always succeeds (no panic) for valid input Ristretto points
• The result is a valid Ristretto point
• The result represents the sum of the inputs (in the context of elliptic curve addition)
-/

1.) Merge the information under "natural language description" into the module docstring (= the comment block right after the imports that starts with /-! # Spec Theorem for `RistrettoPoint::add` ...) in a suitable, elegant, and information-preserving manner. Sometimes a module docstring containts an expression of the form "Specification and proof for [...]"; remove this, as it is redundant. Also, do not announce "Natural language description:" or something like that in the module docstring, just directly give the mathematical natural-language description of the function directly in the module docstring after the title. IMPORTANT: If the "Natural language description" in the central comment block contains a bulleted list with MORE information than the current module docstring, then put ALL information from this bulleted list (in the form of another bulleted list) into the central comment block into the module docstring in an orderly and useful manner; do not drop any valuable natural-language information about the function!

2.) Move the information under "natural languages specs" into the spec theorem docstring via a bulleted list of the proven properties (= the comment block right above the actual spec theorem that starts with /-- **Spec and proof concerning ...).** Often, the precise NL specs are anyway already there, so no need to do anything then. Aim for one bullet-point / line for the no-panic condition, and then for one bullet-point/ line each for post_condition_1, ..., post_condition_n. While one line / bullet-point per post_condition is the desirable standard, and it should always be done this way if it is naturally possible, this is somewhat of a soft requirement, and it is sometimes allowed to collapse several post_conditions into one line / bullet-point if this is the more natural approach (but only if one post_condition per bullet-point / line is truly less natural than this).

3.) Then delete the central comment block

So ultimately, each spec theorem file should have

- a module docstring containing a mathematical natural-language description of  the function outlining purpose and mathematical background, and
- a spec theorem docstring listing a precise, natural-language description of the specs in a bulleted list (one line for each post_condition_i)
- no central comment block anymore

This way we will retain all information but get rid of repetition in the spec theorem file!

### Where / how to place "open" and "namespace"

After the end of the module docstring, which looks something like

  Source: "rust/source/path.rs"
  -/

add an empty line, then add

open Aeneas Aeneas.Std Result Aeneas.Std.WP

and then immediately below that, add something akin to

namespace "appropriate namespace for the function associated with the spec theorem as oulined above"

Then after the end of the proof of the spec theorem, add one more empty line, and then add something akin to

end "appropriate namespace for the function associated with the spec theorem as oulined above"

to appropriately close the namespace again!

Additional note: sometimes, between the 

open Aeneas Aeneas.Std Result Aeneas.Std.WP

and the

namespace "appropriate namespace for the function associated with the spec theorem as oulined above"

there can be an additional line of the form

open [...]

that opens other approproate namespaces! This additional, separate "open" command is allowed!

Another additional note: sometimes helper theorems and helper lemmas are between the last open statement but before the namespace statement; this is fine too!

### Full, precise filepaths

In spec theorem files, always use the full Rust path (crate + all module segments + function name, e.g. `curve25519_dalek::ristretto::RistrettoPoint::add`) in both the module docstring (# Spec theorem for ...) and the theorem docstring (/-- **Spec theorem for ...** -/).

### Removal / avoidance of redundant prefixes

IMPORTANT: Always use the shortest unambiguous name for every identifier: any prefix already resolved by an enclosing "namespace" declaration or an "open" statement is redundant and must be avoided / removed!

